owl:Ontology.rdfs:comment:
Changes for 0.3:
- Added data property IMDb_ID - Removed Movie as domain from data properties 'duration' and 'length' because these are also used in Classification instances. - Added Text-class with subclasses to store text data. These entities can be used to store further analyses of the actual texts, like lemmatization and NER.
ontology has been originally created in order to store and process the Elonet movie metadata from the National Audiovisual Institute of Finland.
owl:Ontology.rdfs:label: Ontology for MoMaF project

owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment: Property used to link digital objects to media entities.
Links any sublass of "Text" to anything. Is used for storing text data that can be processed further in the connected Text subclass entity.

owl:DatatypeProperty.rdfs:comment: Contains the respective IMDb ID for the node. Is relevant for Movies and Persons, at least.
Created for systematicizing Elonet data.
Size of audience
Award won
"Place" of the Broadcast, i.e., TV Channel
Number of film copies
Date of the Datable that has this property. (See subclasses of Datable)
id string that has both he data type and number
On purpose, the format is same as for Wikidata property P2346 so the content can be used to link to Wikidata.
On purpose, this is similar in format as the Wikidata property P2387 so the contents of this field can be used to link to Wikidata.
Countries to which the film has been exported
Used for annotations. The number of the first frame for which this annotation is valid.
Frame height in pixels, of DigitalFilmFile
Frame width in pixels, of a DigitalFilmFile
Frames per second, as double, of DigitalFilmFile.
"Academic" commentary of the film. Has contextualizing information about the film its production process, etc.
Content Description of the film.
Samples of reviews of the film.
Plot synopsis
Media number. Same as the number from Elonet ID:s, but exists only for media entities.
Estimated income (at the theatres?)
Used for annotations. The number of the last frame for which this annotation is valid.
Contains the lemmatized version of the text in ":text" property of the same entity.
Music of the film
Original idea for the film
Original work on which the film is based
Score describing the quality or goodness of match behind this annotation. A measure of reliability, a decimal between 0 and 1
National Filmography ID
Sound system used in the film. A free-text field.
Created for systematizing Elonet data
The location (preferably URL) of the media file, if exists/known.
Contains the text content of a "Text" class entity.

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: This is an actor role, i.e., members of this class are resonsible for creating the adaptation.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: adaptation
sovitus

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: An administrative name used to locate things. Name of a country, administrative region, city, town, commune, etc. Could be used to link to entities with same name in Wikidata or the SAPO ontology,
A general superclass for different types of agents that could be involved in the movie making process. See subclasses (Company, Group, Person).
Superclass for annotations. Should not be used directly for any object.
Broadcast event for Movie. has data properties describing the boradcast event.
Movie classification by rating agency. Has various data properties reflecting the data recorded for the classification instance.
A company or other non-human legal entity.
Everything with a date. This class in used only as a domain for the data property "date"
A generic superclass for free-text filming location descriptions. Can be used as node type in order to retrieve all free-text filming location descriptions (see subclasses).
A genre classification term.
A group of individual humans appearing together under a common name: a band, a group of musician, a troupe.
Superclass for all media types.
A moveitype term (Documentary, Fiction, etx.)
An individual human person in the Elonet database.
A generic superclass for everything that has a place, esp. Adminplace.

Member of the movie production.
This is the most generic class, and contains production members for which a more specific class could not be deduced from the original data. Can be used in queries as node type to retrieve all members of the movie production, including companies, groups, and documented non-credited members. See subclasses for more refined definitions.
Subject matter terms describing the content and themes of the movie.
Superclass for all text data classes. Should not be used directly.
Unknown, not identified or otherwise undefinable members of the movie production.
A superclass for different vocabularies that are used to describe and classigy movies.
